<div class="wp-forum-connect-featured">

    <h2 class="comments-title">Promoted Comments</h2>

    <div class="wp-forum-connect-comment-list">

                <article class="wp-forum-connect-comment">

            <div class="wp-forum-connect-comment-avatar">

                <img alt="" src="https://arstechnica.com/wp-content/plugins/article-forum-connect/public/img/avatar.png" srcset="https://arstechnica.com/wp-content/plugins/article-forum-connect/public/img/avatar.png 2x" class="avatar avatar-60 photo" height="60" width="60" loading="lazy">

            </div>

            <div class="wp-forum-connect-comment-message">

                <div>

                    <b class="fn"><a href="https://arstechnica.com/civis/members/stormcrash.447219/" target="_blank">stormcrash</a></b>

                </div>

                <div>

                    For all those saying that the non chinese automakers should &quot;just compete harder&quot; I have a little tale for you. One that happened entirely in a single domestic market so there's no foreign policy distortions too.<br />
<br />
At the turn of the 2000's there was a company called AT&amp;T Corp (which is not the same as today's AT&amp;T Inc) that was seeing its market share and profit being obliterated by cheaper competitors in the long distance market. AT&amp;T competed harder and harder, they cut costs, laid off staff to the bone, slashed investment in network infrastructure all to lower costs to match their competitors on price, and they were still losing money and coming out more expensive. There was strong temptation to fudge the numbers but they refused, their pride on the line.<br />
<br />
Well it turned out that the reason they're competitors were so much cheaper was that they were all cooking the books and all went down burning in scandal, MCI-Worldcom, Global Crossing, etc. As their competitors burned AT&amp;T briefly thought they had won, thanking their people for &quot;saving the company&quot; by keeping the books honest. But while they didn't sink in scandal the damage had wounded them mortally. To raise capital they had sold their future by spinning off AT&amp;T Broadband and AT&amp;T Wireless to cut the debt from acquiring them in the first place. In the end they were left with an underinvested shrinking long distance segment and were bought a few years later by what had once been a subsidiary, SBC Communications, once known as Southwestern Bell.<br />
<br />
You can't compete fairly against someone who is cheating, all you will do is self immolate and sell your future just to stay in the game a little bit longer, just to watch your chips bleed away
                </div>

                <div>

                    <a href="https://arstechnica.com/civis/posts/42825683/" target="_blank">

                        <time datetime="2024-05-13T17:21:14+00:00">May 13, 2024 at 5:21 pm</time>

                    </a>

                </div>

            </div>

        </article>
                <article class="wp-forum-connect-comment">

            <div class="wp-forum-connect-comment-avatar">

                <img alt="" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/civis/data/avatars/m/501/501263.jpg?1700185051" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/civis/data/avatars/l/501/501263.jpg?1700185051 2x" class="avatar avatar-60 photo" height="60" width="60" loading="lazy">

            </div>

            <div class="wp-forum-connect-comment-message">

                <div>

                    <b class="fn"><a href="https://arstechnica.com/civis/members/gaballard.501263/" target="_blank">gaballard</a></b>

                </div>

                <div>

                    Because a lot of people have a hard time separating a people from their government, it’s worth reiterating…<br />
<br />
The Chinese Communist Party is not the Chinese people, their culture, or their history.<br />
<br />
Being critical of the CCP’s economic and political policies is not the same as being critical of the Chinese people, their culture, or their history.<br />
<br />
Being critical of the CCP is a rational outlook towards a government that has positioned themselves as a major geopolitical rival, that engages in systemic human rights violations, and is contributing more to climate change than almost anyone else on Earth.<br />
<br />
Being critical of the Chinese people as an ethnicity, culture, and so on, purely because they are Chinese, is racist and sinophobic.
                </div>

                <div>

                    <a href="https://arstechnica.com/civis/posts/42825924/" target="_blank">

                        <time datetime="2024-05-13T18:22:43+00:00">May 13, 2024 at 6:22 pm</time>

                    </a>

                </div>

            </div>

        </article>
                <article class="wp-forum-connect-comment">

            <div class="wp-forum-connect-comment-avatar">

                <img alt="" src="https://arstechnica.com/wp-content/plugins/article-forum-connect/public/img/avatar.png" srcset="https://arstechnica.com/wp-content/plugins/article-forum-connect/public/img/avatar.png 2x" class="avatar avatar-60 photo" height="60" width="60" loading="lazy">

            </div>

            <div class="wp-forum-connect-comment-message">

                <div>

                    <b class="fn"><a href="https://arstechnica.com/civis/members/android_alpaca.390603/" target="_blank">android_alpaca</a></b>

                </div>

                <div>

                    <blockquote class="xfBb-quote" data-name="elty">Ars is weird.<br />
<br />
If United States is investing green technology and makes it cheaper for everyone, then it would be great for climate change and humanity.<br />
<br />
If China is doing the same?  Oh it would be better to protect companies that only aim for short term profit by producing gigantic SUV and truck.</blockquote>China is not doing the same thing as US and European governments. If China restricted it's investments to per-car subsidies, tax breaks for factories, and incentives to meet certain emissions targets like other nations, that would be great! I will note that US and European EV subsidies actually apply to <i>any</i> automakers making and/or selling vehicles in their countries (e.g. German, Swedish, Japanese, Korean manufacturers are also getting per-car subsidies as well as factory subsidies) in contrast to the problematic direct cash infusions China is doing.<br />
<br />
But China not doing what every other nation is doing, it is directly funneling billions of dollars into Chinese-only companies to allow them to selling EV at a loss basically in order to gain marketshare and monopolize the market. Ignoring that fact and not considering what happens <i>after</i> Chinese companies have a monopoly on EV   is very short-sighted thinking and missing the long term consequence of accepting <i>any means</i> to an end. I mean what't he harm in offering <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2007%E2%80%932008_financial_crisis" target="_blank" class="link link--external" rel="nofollow ugc noopener">people in 2007 an no-money down adjustable rate mortgage</a> to make is cheaper for people to own a home, am I right. It would be great for home-ownership and the American dream!<br />
<br />
I actually think BYD and Nio are interesting companies and I don't begrudge them for accepting free money from the Chinese government, but in terms of international trade, I think some attempts should be made to prevent China for temporarily manipulating the markets (although I don't know if Biden's 100% tariff is the correct solution to the problem). If you want to see the fallout of the Chinese government supercharging an industry... take a look at their real estate market (e.g. the city of Ordos has millions of empty homes). Or this $100B city in Malaysia.<br />
<br />
<span data-s9e-mediaembed="youtube"><span><iframe loading="lazy" allowfullscreen="" scrolling="no" style="background:url(https://i.ytimg.com/vi/D0PxRxwTa50/hqdefault.jpg) 50% 50% / cover" src="https://www.youtube-nocookie.com/embed/D0PxRxwTa50"></iframe></span></span>
                </div>

